        "last_activity_date": 1459868764,
        "creation_date": 1459868260,
        "answer_count": 2,
        "title": "Installing jre locally in windows app directory",
        "body": "<p>I have a question about deploying windows application with java module.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have windows application with several modules. One of these modules is written in java and is packaged as jar-archive. And if there's need for using this module, the application ask jre to start execute this jar.\nFor this time during application installation it's initialized jre installation.<\/p>\n\n<p>I would like to understand the following.\nIs it possible to install during application installation silently install jre in the application directory. So it jre copy could be used by the application.<\/p>\n\n<p>I'm talking about structure like this:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>/app\n/app/jre\n/app/modules/myModule.jar\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>So if it's needed to run myModule.jar I could do it with java from app/jre/bin ?<\/p>\n\n<p>I saw something like that at Spark messenger (<a href=\"http://www.igniterealtime.org/projects/spark/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.igniterealtime.org/projects/spark/<\/a>). This application uses its own jre, which is installed at /Spark/jre/. But as I understand, this application is written in java and builded as a windows distributive using install4j.<\/p>\n\n<p>I tried to find the answer to my question, but maybe I'm doing something wrong, I always find a solution of creating an exe-wrapper for jar file.<\/p>\n\n<p>I would like to know about possibility to deploy application with installing jre locally in application folder.<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 36429997,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "windows",
            "jar"
        ],
        "score": 2,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 493
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1b5d1c323f0706e734372a836c4fb8aa?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 1360233,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1297749,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1297749/devendra-bhatte",
                "reputation": 358,
                "display_name": "Devendra Bhatte"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459868616,
            "creation_date": 1459868616,
            "body": "<p>You could ideally have used Java Web Start in the past.\nCurrently, you can use javapackager.\n<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/tools/windows/javapackager.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/technotes/tools/windows/javapackager.html<\/a><\/p>\n\n<p>The javapackager command allows developers to create standalone native install bundles that do not require a separate JRE installation. The native options include: installer, image, exe, msi, dmg, rpm, and deb.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is ideal for desktop applications, where the user may not have their own JRE installed and just wants the program to run.  It may not be appropriate for server-based applications where an administrator would want full control over the environment.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"https://blogs.oracle.com/java-platform-group/entry/java_web_start_in_or\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://blogs.oracle.com/java-platform-group/entry/java_web_start_in_or<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430122,
            "question_id": 36429997
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1ed234232e973448b96bdf88a9a12810?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 7968176,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 6013804,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/6013804/jgreven",
                "reputation": 33,
                "display_name": "JGreven"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 0,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1459868764,
            "creation_date": 1459868764,
            "body": "<p>In your /app/jre/bin folder there should be an executable binary called java. So in your folder /app/modules you can run <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>/app/jre/bin/java -jar myModule.jar\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>That should work.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 36430178,
            "question_id": 36429997
        }
    ],
